<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="37.[264,1323,471,977]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
Diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName box="[396,600,471,496]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Anopinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurea">
<emphasis box="[396,600,471,496]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Anopinella aurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[972,1120,471,496]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Anopinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phillipsae">
<emphasis box="[972,1120,471,496]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. phillipsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a pale subterminal line; however, it has a considerably greater forewing length and a much lighter ground color. The subbasally bent uncus, enlarged distal lobes of the gnathos, and distally attenuate valva are similar to several other species in the 
<taxonomicName box="[927,984,591,617]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Anopinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fana">Fana</taxonomicName>
Species Group (e.g., 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Anopinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phillipsae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. phillipsae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[350,462,631,656]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Anopinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="larana">
<emphasis box="[350,462,631,656]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. larana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The densely spiculate corpus bursae, with spiculae extending posterad into the ductus bursae, also is characteristic of several species in the 
<taxonomicName box="[1084,1141,671,697]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Anopinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fana">Fana</taxonomicName>
Species Group (e.g., 
<taxonomicName box="[337,454,711,736]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Anopinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="larana">
<emphasis box="[337,454,711,736]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. larana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[475,633,711,736]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Anopinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis box="[475,633,711,736]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">A. brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). A complete description, illustrations of the male and female genitalia, and a color illustration of the adult can be found in 
<bibRefCitation author="Razowski" pageId="37" pageNumber="56" refString="Razowski, J. &amp; Becker, V. O. (2000.) Description of three North Andean genera of Euliini and their seven species. SHILAP Revista Lepidopterologia, 28, 109 - 117." type="journal article" year="2000">
Razowski and Becker (
<number box="[273,338,791,817]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
